= Dzogchen Guru Yoga: an Introduction and Sadhana

November 9, 2025

https://youtu.be/5vhmWHhf6ow?si=cuGaLkFz3isRqJnb

(transcribed up to 21:00 when the actual sadhana begins)

In Vajrayana, it's very typical to use guru yoga to begin to warm up to the view.  And this is an approach used, probably, in countless methodologies.  So, just like I said before, that would be like me counting mantras: "Om Ah Hung Benza Guru Pema Siddhi Hung, Om Ah Hung Benza Guru Pema Siddhi Hung - Please enlighten me, please save me."  It's a soteriological approach, really. 
But some teachers, if people are lucky, they get to hear, that you're actually starting to create the basis for awareness.  Because we don't even entertain the fact that we could be fully enlightened, pure beings.  For some of us, it's a no-go.  It's unacceptable.  So when you start to imagine yourself as Buddha Shakyamuni, or Guru Rinpoche, or any of these, now you have the landing place for the blessings.  Now you can say, "Yeah, I can abide in enlightenment", and it gives a kind of internal archetype confidence, that's...Archetypes are proven in modern days, to be very powerful.

So that's the idea, okay?  If you're taking a typical Vajrayana approach, you would be chanting these mantras and doing visualizations:  Kyerim and Dzogrim.

In this approach, I don't teach guru yoga sadhanas, I don't do them very often, because the emphasis is on awareness. Which may seem like overzealous, overconfident or something like that, and I totally would understand people looking at it like that, but that's just how we roll here, and we just are taking the top-down approach.  

So, when we're  resting in awareness, and we're doing this guru yoga,  it starts off with a kind of praise to the three kayas as our teachers, so it shows you, in this very first part---it says 'I, and motherly sentient beings equal to space, pray to the dharmakaya guru.'  That's the emptiness aspect of your own awareness, okay?  So it can sound externalized, and even theistic, but this is a dzogchen sadhana. And maybe Yeshe will put the Namcho text up there for you.

So this is the first part;  it's called the Fourfold Prayer (but it's more of a song) for Motherly Sentient Beings Equal to Space.  It's on page 129; probably should have given you that.

So the second part is :  'I, and motherly sentient beings equal to space, pray to the great bliss samboghakaya guru.'  That's the clarity aspect---right?---of awareness.  Then, 'I, and motherly sentient beings equal to space, pray to the compassionate nirmanakaya guru.'  So that's your---all the energy.  This whole life, everything we're---the sense world---is mind, but very difficult to assess that, when we're within it.  That'd be like an actor in a movie, zooming out and saying, "Wait, this whole thing is a movie!" and seeing the cameraman and everything, right?  That's the power of awareness, anyway. 

So the last one would be:  'I, and motherly sentient beings equal to space, pray to the guru, the precious buddha.'  So this is important right here.  I  think it's great if we can have archetypes, if we can have people in our nirmanakaya life that we look up to, that when we think of them we feel cared for, we feel like they only want us to be free.  And so in this regard you start to warm up to whoever it is for you.  It could be your mom, it could be a teacher in school, it could be a spiritual guide---I want you to tune in to your spiritual heritage here, because you have it.  And you have a lineage.  It may not be Guru Rinpoche and Khenchen Tsewang Gyatso and Dawai Gocha, right?  It may be other mandalas here.  And that's the beauty of these online gatherings, is that we have this really diverse...Mandala is essentially a collective of beings that you'll run into them lifetime after lifetime and things like that.

So this is going deep into the dharma, and perhaps getting even a little axiomatic, in the fact that there are some prerequisites to understand.  But if you can just keep two things in mind here:  that when we do these mantras, it's possible for you to begin to smell, feel, taste, hear, this wonderful Pure Land; it just comes.  Mmhmm.  And that's the minds of the teachers.  All these great yogis:  Longchenpa, Guru Padmasambhava, their minds have not died.  

And Guru Padmasambhava, as much as I would like to stay pure dzogchen on you all the time, I have to say, was my first teacher, like my father, without even being there.  I had to rely on this invisible relationship.  And  that may not be accessible to everybody, right, but I think some of you can resonate.  This is my main teacher; like, no bull, okay?  The visions I've had with Guru Padmasambhava I don't even talk about, they're so precious.  I'm scared to oversaturate them.  

So I'm saying this, only putting it out there because this could happen with you.  You could feel a great kinship with the lineage in some way or another.  Khenchen Tsewang Gyatso is the same; Penor Rinpoche  ---they are here with me.  Which is why I live the life of a renunciate, and have given myself over to the dharma.  You don't have to do that.  You can live your life, do your thing; I'm doing that, so that I can keep the dharma going, so that you can be free in your life.  But you don't have to become a wide-eyed weirdo like me, okay?

So, this is the most important, summoning this spirit of the guru, which is awareness itself, which is the great tathagathagarbha, the dharmadhatu, enlightened mind, this tremendous ineffability, majestic, heavenly landscape that we begin to invoke through resting in awareness, and chanting non-conceptual mantras.  You don't have to chant them, even.  Allow awareness, allow the conditioning to come off of you, so that you can see a little bit of---what's here.  

So that's the three kayas that we start out with.  Then there's another section here where we say 'lama khyen no', and "lama khyen no" means "lama, care for me."  And indeed, over the years, there have been many beings that just, when they feel down and out, particularly in a spiritual context, or something like that, they really just, within awareness:  'Lama khyen no, lama khyen no,' "care for me", right?  "Be my friend on this path."  So it's a very beautiful invocation...

And then after that, we go into a Seven-Line Prayer.  Yeah, I was just thinking that [SANGHA 1] is not here, and he was asking about this introduction.  Maybe he could not make it.  But---all right.

So, the Seven-Line Prayer actually has a whole dzogchen explanation of it.  It's not supposed to be understood verbatim.  That's a provisional thing, like all this :  'Born in the heart of a lotus, you are renowned as the lotus-born, surrounded by a retinue of many'---it would be dakas and dakinis, males and females, or they would actually be more androgynous, and then---'following in your footsteps, I pray to you, please come forth and grant your blessings.'  This is again just  invoking awareness more than anything, not the person Guru Rinpoche.  If we were invoking the person Guru Rinpoche, you wouldn't know what to invoke. He's in the 8th Century---do you really know who that is?  But you can know who Guru Rinpoche is through awareness, because he took the fruit as the path too. And so, a lot of you have come here with Guru Padmasambhava connections.  Even [SANGHA 2] right now, has an image [ as their profile photo]  of Guru Padmasambhava.

